ominent federal officials====\n* [[Howard Baker|Howard Henry Baker Jr.]], 1945, U.S. Senate majority leader, White House chief of staff, U.S. ambassador to Japan (R)<ref name=\"Howard Baker\"/> \n* [[Donald Ensenat]], Law, 1973, White House chief of protocol{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n* [[Lisa P. Jackson]], Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency (D)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lisa P. Jackson|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/661/000180121/|publisher=Notable Names Data Base|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> (2009-2013)\n* [[Stephen Douglas Johnson]], AB '85, L '88, U.S. House Chief Counsel for Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit(1995\u201398) and Bush White House Senior Advisor to the Office of Federal Housing Oversight (2001\u201303)<ref>Claire Chapman. ''NAIC Hires Veteran House Counsel as Its Lawyer'' Insurance Regulator, Vo.8, No. 42, November 3, 1997, P. 3 - one of the few articles which mentions Johnson's full education, e.g., University of Hamburg, Tulane University, Tulane Law School, and Boston University School of Law</ref>\n\n====Diplomats====\n* [[Howard Baker|Howard Henry Baker Jr.]] (1945), U.S. Senate majority leader, White House chief of staff, U.S. ambassador to Japan (R)<ref name=\"Howard Baker\"/> \n* [[Kristie Kenney]], G '79, U.S. Ambassador to Thailand, former ambassador to the Philippines and Ecuador <ref>{{cite web|title=Kristie Kenney |url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/68599.htm |publisher=U.S. Department State |accessdate=25 January 2013 }}</ref> \n* [[John Giffen Weinmann]], (A&S \u201950, L \u201952), former U.S. Ambassador to Finland and chief of protocol in the White House     \n* [[Clint Williamson]], (L '86) U.S. Ambassador-at-large for war crimes issues, UN envoy, White House policy official\n\n====Mayors====\n* [[Sidney Barthelemy]], mayor of New Orleans (D)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sidney Barthelemy|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/100/000162611/|publisher=Notable Names Data Base|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Capdevielle]], Law, mayor of New Orleans<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul Capdevielle|url=http://www.storyvilledistrictnola.com/neworleans_mayors.html|publisher=storyvilledistrictnola.com|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> \n* [[Ray Nagin]], M.B.A. 1994, mayor of New Orleans (D)\n* [[Robert Poydasheff]], Law, former mayor of Columbus, Georgia (2003\u20132007) (R)\n* [[Jerry Springer]], B.A. 1965, former mayor of [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] and television personality\n* [[T. Semmes Walmsley]], Law, mayor of New Orleans (D)\n* [[Sandra Frankel]], (n\u00e9e Applebaum), 1963, Arts and Sciences, former mayor of the Town of Brighton, NY (D)\n\n====City and state officials====\n* [[Joseph Bouie Jr.]], Master of Social Work, member of the [[Louisiana House of Representatives]] for District 97 in Orleans Parish since 2014 (D)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_Reps/members.asp?ID=97 |title=Joseph Bouie Jr. |publisher=house.louisiana.gov |accessdate=April 26, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428022834/http://house.louisiana.gov/H_Reps/members.asp?ID=97 |archivedate=April 28, 2015 }}</ref>  \n* [[Timothy Burns (Louisiana politician)|Timothy G. Burns]], B.A. 1979, M.B.A. 1980, J.D. 1983, Louisiana state representative from St. Tammany Parish since 2004 (R){{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n* [[Buddy Caldwell]], attorney general of Louisiana since 2008; former district attorney in [[Tallulah, Louisiana|Tallulah]] (D)-turned-(R){{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n*[[Philip Ciaccio]], state representative, New Orleans City Council member, state circuit judge from 1982 to 1998<ref>{{cite news|url=http://obits.nola.com/obituaries/nola/obituary.aspx?n=philip-charles-ciaccio&pid=176486531&fhid=5630|title=Philip Charles Ciaccio|newspaper=[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]|accessdate=November 14, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[John Elton Coon]], state representative from [[Ouachita Parish, Louisiana|Ouachita Parish]]; the mayor of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]] from 1949 to 1956, and state fire marshal from 1956 to 1964 (D)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Tulane_University_Jambalaya_Yearbook/1929/Page_149.html|title=Tulane University, Freshman Class of 1929, p. 149|publisher=e-yearbook.com|accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Eddie Doucet]], former state representative for Jefferson Parish<ref>\"Louisiana: Doucet, Eddie A.\", ''Who's Who in American Politics, 2003-2004'', 19th ed., Vol. 1 (Alabama-Montana) (Marquis Who's Who: [[New Providence, New Jersey|New Providence]], [[New Jersey]], 2003), p. 777</ref> \n* [[Frank Fulco]], state representative from Shreveport; leader of Italian American community in Louisiana (D)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Tulane_University_Jambalaya_Yearbook/1929/Page_149.html|title=Tulane University, Freshman Class of 1929, p. 149|publisher=e-yearbook.com|accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Cameron Henry]], member of Louisiana House (R){{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n* [[Nita Hutter|Nita Rusich Hutter]], M. Ed. 1978, state representative from St. Bernard Parish (R)<ref>{{cite web|title=Nita Hutter|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/54284/nita-hutter#.UQHTdidZWBE|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> \n* [[Adam Kwasman]], B.A. Economics 2003, member of Arizona House of Representatives District 11; 2014 candidate for U.S. Congress (R)\n* [[Elwyn Nicholson]], state senator from Jefferson Parish from 1972 to 1988 (D)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.nola.com/nola_daily_obits_newsletter/2014/10/former_sen_elwyn_nicholson_wes.html|title=Sen. Elwyn Nicholson, a West Bank grocer, Jean Lafitte National Park proponent, dies at 90|author=Andrea Shawdate=October 10, 2014|newspaper=[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]|accessdate=October 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023004810/http://blog.nola.com/nola_daily_obits_newsletter/2014/10/former_sen_elwyn_nicholson_wes.html|archive-date=Octob